-- Charming Shoppes cuts profit forecast
-- 
-- Mon Jun 25, 2007 11:51am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/06/25/businesspro-charmingshoppes-outlook-dc-idUSN2529598220070625

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - Apparel retailer Charming Shoppes Inc. 
CHRS.O cut its profit forecast on Monday, citing lower sales 
and an increase in markdowns spring merchandise. 

  The retailer, which specializes in plus-size women's 
apparel, said it expects second-quarter earnings of 18 cents to 
20 cents a share, down from a previous forecast of 25 cents to 
27 cents.  The owner of the Lane Bryant and Fashion Bug chains 
forecast consolidated comparable-store sales in its retail 
stores segment would be flat to down by a low-single-digit 
percentage in the second quarter, and flat to up by a 
low-single-digit percentage for the year.  Charming Shoppes said it expects full-year earnings of 80 
cents to 82 cents a share, down from a previous forecast of 86 
cents to 90 cents.  Analysts on average expect second-quarter earnings of 26 
cents a share and a full-year profit of 90 cents a share, 
according to Reuters Estimates.  Bensalem, Pennsylvania-based Charming Shoppes said it 
expects second-quarter sales of $785 million to $795 million 
and full-year sales of $3.15 billion to $3.20 billion.  Analysts on average expect second-quarter sales of $791.11 
million and full-year sales of $3.2 billion.  The company said it expects to complete its share 
repurchase program at the higher end of the $80 million to $100 
million range.  (Reporting by  Sarah Coffey )